## Working Rules

1. Preserve the selected architecture style.
2. Keep generated code complete, but avoid unused abstractions, dependencies, modules, imports, providers, environment variables, and Docker services.
3. Prefer focused, incremental edits over broad rewrites.
4. After code changes, run the smallest relevant verification first, then broader checks when the change crosses module boundaries.
5. Do not add a new ORM, cache, queue, auth strategy, or documentation system unless the user asks for that technology.
6. Treat `.skelenest/project.json`, this skill, and `package.json` as the source of truth for selected-stack decisions.

## Architecture Guidance

<%_ if (selections.architecture === 'standard') { _%>
This project uses the standard NestJS module style.

- Place feature code under `src/<feature>`.
- Keep controllers thin: parse transport inputs, call services, return DTO-shaped outputs.
- Put business behavior in services and keep persistence details behind clear private methods or repository classes when complexity grows.
- Keep DTOs under `src/<feature>/dto` and tests near the code they cover.
- Wire controllers, services, guards, and providers in the owning feature module. Do not create cross-feature imports unless there is a real dependency.
<%_ } else if (selections.architecture === 'clean') { _%>
This project uses Clean Architecture.

- Keep presentation concerns under `presentation`, application behavior under `application`, and adapters under `infrastructure`.
- Application services and use cases may depend on ports, DTOs, and domain/application types; they must not import Prisma, TypeORM, Sequelize, Redis, HTTP decorators, or Nest request objects.
- Infrastructure adapters implement application ports and translate ORM/cache/queue records into application-facing objects.
- Presentation code owns controllers, guards, strategies, pipes, and request/response DTO mapping.
- Register port tokens and their concrete adapters in the module file closest to the feature.
<%_ } else if (selections.architecture === 'ddd') { _%>
This project uses DDD plus Clean Architecture.

- Use `src/modules/<bounded-context>` as the default feature boundary.
- Keep entities, value objects, domain services, domain events, and invariants in `domain`.
- Keep use cases, application services, ports, and application DTOs in `application`.
- Keep persistence, cache, queue, mail, token, and external-service adapters in `infrastructure`.
- Keep controllers, guards, strategies, decorators, and HTTP DTOs in `presentation`.
- Domain code must be framework-agnostic: no Nest decorators, ORM models, Prisma types, HTTP types, or environment access.
- Repositories should persist aggregate roots and expose intention-revealing methods such as `findByEmail`, `save`, `existsBySlug`, and `softDelete`.
- Do not split every small function into a use case. Add use cases when there is a user/business action, transaction boundary, authorization decision, or orchestration.
<%_ } _%>

## Persistence Rules

<%_ if (selections.orm === 'prisma') { _%>
Prisma is the selected ORM.

- Use `PrismaService` and generated Prisma client types only in infrastructure/persistence code or standard-feature services that already own persistence.
- Keep schema changes in `prisma/schema.prisma`; run generate after every schema edit and create a migration when the persisted shape changes.
- Use camelCase field names in TypeScript and map database column names to snake_case with `@map`, for example `createdAt DateTime @default(now()) @map("created_at")`.
- Add audit fields to new persisted models unless there is a strong reason not to:
  - `createdAt DateTime @default(now()) @map("created_at")`
  - `updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt @map("updated_at")`
  - `deletedAt DateTime? @map("deleted_at")`
- Add `@@map("<snake_case_plural_table>")` to models unless the existing schema uses another convention.
- Prefer soft delete for user/business-owned records: set `deletedAt` instead of deleting rows, filter reads with `deletedAt: null`, and keep restore/hard-delete behavior explicit.
- Keep unique indexes compatible with soft delete. When a value must be reusable after deletion, use a composite uniqueness strategy or an explicit database migration/index rather than a naive `@unique` that blocks recreation.
- Do not use Prisma models as domain entities in Clean/DDD code. Map records at the repository boundary.
- Use transactions for multi-write invariants and pass the transaction client through private helpers instead of opening nested transactions.
- Select only fields needed by the caller for read paths that can grow large; avoid broad `include` trees by default.
- Do not add TypeORM or Sequelize code.
<%_ } else if (selections.orm === 'typeorm') { _%>
TypeORM is the selected ORM.

- Use `TypeOrmModule`, repositories, and entities under `src/database/entities` or the architecture-specific infrastructure folder.
- Keep database column names snake_case with explicit `name` options, for example `@CreateDateColumn({ name: 'created_at' })`.
- Add `createdAt`, `updatedAt`, and `deletedAt` to new persistent entities unless the table is intentionally immutable.
- Prefer `softDelete`/`softRemove` and queries that exclude deleted rows by default.
- Keep entity decorators out of DDD domain entities; map between persistence entities and domain/application models at adapters.
- Use migrations for schema changes; do not rely on `synchronize` outside throwaway local development.
- Do not add Prisma or Sequelize code.
<%_ } else if (selections.orm === 'sequelize') { _%>
Sequelize is the selected ORM.

- Use `SequelizeModule` and `sequelize-typescript` models under `src/database/models` or the architecture-specific infrastructure folder.
- Keep table and column names explicit with snake_case names.
- Enable timestamps for normal business models and map them to `created_at` and `updated_at`.
- Use paranoid models for soft delete when records should be recoverable or auditable.
- Keep Sequelize models out of DDD domain code; map at infrastructure boundaries.
- Do not add Prisma or TypeORM code.
<%_ } else { _%>
- No ORM was selected. Do not add database clients, migrations, repositories, or `DATABASE_URL` unless the user asks to introduce persistence.
<%_ } _%>

